subSection.paragraph:
Biogeographic transition zones are areas of overlap, located between two different biogeographic regions (Morrone 2006, 2015a; 
Ferro & Morrone 2014
). Transition zones function as natural laboratories, since they present a gradient of replacement and segregation among biotic groups with different evolutionary origins (Morrone 2006, 2015a, 2020; 
Ferro & Morrone 2014
). The following transition zones are recognized globally (
Morrone 2015a
): Chinese (Palearctic-Oriental transition), Indo-Malayan (Oriental-Australian transition), Mexican (Nearctic-Neotropical transition), Saharo-Arabian (Palearctic-Ethiopian transition) and South American (Neotropical-Andean transition). The Mexican Transition Zone (MTZ) is recognized as a particularly complex area, since it hosts a wide variety of ecosystems, climates and orographic systems, as well as a high species richness and a considerable number of endemisms (
Ferro & Morrone 2014
; 

Morrone 2015 
b

, 2019, 2020; Halffter 2017, 2019; 
Halffter & Morrone, 2017
).

The classic explanation that separates the Nearctic and Neotropical regions with a border in Mesoamerica, often does not fit to the distribution and evolutionary history of the entomofauna in this region ( Halffter 1964 ; Morrone 2014 , 2015b ). Therefore, the current theory of the MTZ has been particularly useful to explain the biogeography of insects. Halffter (1962 , 1964 , 1978 , 1987 ) initially used the term “dispersal patterns” to define those biological elements that formed the biogeographic scheme of the MTZ. Later,
Halffter et al . (1995)
applied the term “distributional patterns”, since the biotic elements present in the MTZ are not determined exclusively by the phenomenon of dispersal, but also by vicariance. For this study we use “distributional pattern” to describe the current distribution of a cenocron within the MTZ. Therefore, distributional patterns here represent hypotheses regarding the current distribution and biogeographic history of the biota (Halffter 2017, 2019; Halffter & Morrone 2017 ;
Halffter et al . 2019
). Thus, distributional patterns are considered as hypotheses that can be tested by analytical methods, such as phylogenetic inference and ancestral areas reconstruction.

First, we comment on the distributional patterns of southern origin. 1) Mexican Plateau distribution: This corresponds to the taxa that hypothetically dispersed to the Mexican Plateau during the Cretaceous and late Paleocene prior to the elevation of this geographic area. These taxa subsequently diversified and expanded to the southeastern United States of America and the highlands of Mesoamerica. These taxa prefer open or semi-open habitats with arid or semiarid conditions. It is thought that this is the most ancient Neotropical element of the MTZ (
Halffter 1962
, 
1964
; 
Morrone 2015b
). 2) Mountain Mesoamerican distribution: Taxa that dispersed from South America towards the Central American Nucleus during the Oligocene-Miocene, diversifying together with the tropical mountain cloud forests (
Halffter 1978
, 
1987
; 
Morrone 2015b
). 3) Neotropical Baja Californian distribution: Taxa of Neotropical origin endemic to the Baja California peninsula, which dispersed towards the peninsula during the Miocene prior to the appearance of the Gulf of California. They are typical of xerophytic coastal environments (
Moctezuma & Halffter 2019
). 4) Typical Neotropical distribution: Taxa of South American origin, which hypothetically dispersed towards the MTZ during the Pliocene-Pleistocene, as part of the Great American Biotic Interchange (GABI). They are typical of lowlands and tropical environments present from South America to the coastal plains of the Gulf of Mexico, being particularly diverse in tropical rain forests (
Halffter 1962
, 
1964
; 
Morrone 2015b
).

Below, we list the distributional patterns of northern origin. The Paleoamerican pattern corresponds to Holarctic taxa that hypothetically arrived to North America from Eurasia during the early Cenozoic. These taxa are considered part of the most ancient biota of the MTZ (
Halffter 1987
; 
Morrone 2015b
; 
Halffter & Morrone 2017
) and are divided into six sub-patterns: 1) Relict Paleoamerican: Taxa with a wide distribution in the Old World, which are represented in the MTZ by a reduced number of endemic species with restricted areas of distribution; their distribution is explained as an extreme case of vicariance and subsequent retraction (

Halffter 
et al
. 1995

; 
Halffter & Morrone 2017
; 
Morrone 2015b
). 2) Mountain Paleoamerican: Taxa that successfully colonized the mountains of the MTZ and, to a lesser extent, those of Central America. These taxa have undergone an important process of diversification by vicariance, and are mainly adapted to cold and temperate climatic conditions, but some species may inhabit lowland areas adjacent to the mountains of the MTZ (

Halffter 
et al
. 1995

; 2019; 
Morrone 2015b
; 

Moctezuma 
et al
. 2016

; 
Halffter & Morrone 2017
). 3) Mexican Plateau Paleoamerican: Taxa that diversified on the Mexican High Plateau (

Halffter 
et al
. 2008

; Halffter 2017; 
Halffter & Morrone 2017
). 4) Mesoamerican Paleoamerican: Taxa that diversified in the tropical mountain cloud forests of the Central American Nucleus (
Halffter & Morrone 2017
; 

Halffter 
et al
. 2019

). 5) Paleoamerican Baja Californian: Taxa endemic to the xerophytic and coastal environments of the Baja California peninsula (
Moctezuma & Halffter 2019
). 6) Tropical Paleoamerican: Taxa associated with the tropical and subtropical lowlands (

Halffter 
et al
. 1995

; 
Morrone 2015b
; 
Halffter & Morrone 2017
). The last four Paleoamerican sub-patterns are equivalent in terms of ecology and distribution to the patterns of Neotropical origin (
Halffter & Morrone 2017
). Finally, the Nearctic distributional pattern includes taxa of Holarctic origin or endemic to North America, that dispersed towards the MTZ during the Miocene-Pliocene. These are restricted to cold and temperate zones (
Halffter 1962
, 
1964
, 
1987
; 
Morrone 2015b
).

As stated above, the theory of the MTZ mainly explains the historical biogeography and current distribution of the insects. The Scarabaeinae dung beetles have been the group most widely used for the conceptual development, since they exhibit all the distributional patterns, excepting the Nearctic one. The subfamily Scarabaeinae ( Coleoptera : Scarabaeidae ) comprises approximately 6580 species ( Schoolmeesters 2023 ) and has an almost cosmopolitan distribution (
Nichols et al . 2008
). Current evidence suggests that Scarabaeinae are a monophyletic group (
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
Gunter et al . 2016
; Tarasov & Dimitrov 2016 ;
Dietz et al . 2023
). This group of beetles feeds mainly on dung, but also exhibits saprophagous, necrophagous and, to a lesser extent, predatory habits ( Halffter & Matthews 1966 , Halffter & Halffter 2009 ). The Scarabaeinae contribute to the dynamics of ecosystems with key functions and services, such as cleansing of the ground surface, nutrient cycling, bioturbation and parasite control, among others (
Nichols et al . 2008
;
Beynon et al . 2015
). Given the importance of the Scarabaeinae to our understanding of the MTZ, our aim is to present an evolutionary scenario that allows us to infer the historical biogeography of the MTZ based on the phylogenetic interrelationships of this subfamily. In particular, we test how the taxa that makeup the distributional patterns of the MTZ integrated into an evolutionary, temporal and geographic scenario. Finally, the results obtained are compared with the conceptual framework provided by the theory of the MTZ.

We used four regions of the genome (COI, COII, 16S and ITS), increasing the probability of inferring the phylogeny of the taxa, instead of using only the history of one particular gene or organelle. We used the species
Oscarinus indutilis (Harold, 1874)
of the subfamily Aphodiinae as the most basal out-group, because previous phylogenetic studies suggested that Aphodiinae are the sister group of Scarabaeinae (
Hunter et al . 2007
;
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
McKenna et al . 2015
;
Gunter et al . 2016
; Tarasov & Dimitrov 2016 ;
Dietz et al . 2023
). The complete list of species and the GenBank access numbers for each molecular marker are listed on Table 1 .

DNA was obtained from a small sample of tissue (2 or 3 legs in large individuals, pronotum in small individuals), which was cleaned and examined under the microscope in order to prevent any possible contamination by acari or fungi. The tissue was processed following the protocol of the DNeasy Blood & Tissue kit (QIAGEN). The COI gene was amplified with the primers NANCY (5’-cccggtaaaattaaaatataaacttc-3’) ( Simon et al. 1994 ), HCO-2198 (5´-taaacttcagggtgaccaaaaaatca-3´) and LCO-1490 (5´-ggtcaacaaatcataaagatattgg-3´) (
Folmer et al . 1994
). For COII , we used the primers C1 (5´-ttgattttttggtcayccwgaagt-3´), 3014 (5´-ttcattgcactaatctgccatacta-3´), 3037 (5´- tagtatggcagattagtgcaatgaa-3´) and C2 (5´-ccrcaaatttcwgarcattgacca-3´) (
Simon et al . 1994
;
Takiya et al . 2006
). For 16S, we used the primers LR-J-12887 (5´-ccggtytgaactcaratca-3)´and LR-N-13398 (5´-crmctgtttawcaaaaacat-3´) (
Simon et al . 1994
;
Takiya et al . 2006
). ITS 2 was amplified with ITS 2A (5´-tgtgaactgcaggacacat-3´) and ITS 2B (5´-tatgcttaaattcagggggt-3´) ( Beebe & Saul 1995 ).

Sequences were edited with Sequencher v5 (Gene Codes Corp, Ann Arbor, Michigan) and aligned with BioEdit v7.0.9 (
Hall 1999
). The set of default options was used to produce the best alignment. Subsequently, this alignment was refined with MUSCLE v5 (Edgard 2004) and manually with Mesquite v3.1 (
Maddison & Maddison 2010
). The phylogenetic hypothesis was recovered by Bayesian inference (BI) using MrBayes v3.2.3 (

Ronquist 
et al
. 2012

). The best-fit nucleotide substitution model for each locus was selected using the Akaike information criterion (
Alfaro & Huelsenbeck 2006
) in jMODELTEST v2.0.2 (
Posada 2008
). Monte Carlo Markovian Chains (MCMC) were implemented in two parallel analyses with four chains each (one cold and three hot). Twenty million generations were used for the combined data set. In each case, trees and parameters were sampled every 1000 generations. The majority-rule consensus tree was obtained, with the respective posterior probabilities (PP), after a burn-in discarding the initial 25% of the trees (

Ronquist 
et al
. 2012

).

