FIGURE 2. Chronogram for the Scarabaeinae of the Mexican Transition Zone and related geographic areas (North, Central and South America). Node numbers represent posterior probabilities. Node bars show time uncertainty by means of 95% HPD. Major geological and climatological events related to the MTZ conformation are shown (modified from
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). The main lineages of Scarabaeinae appeared during the Eocene-Oligocene, before the MTZ had reached its current geographic configuration. During the Miocene, the greatest stage of diversification was seen and the orographic systems of the MTZ reached their current configuration.

subSection.paragraph:
Undoubtedly, the biogeography of the Scarabaeinae dung beetles from the MTZ (and the New World) represents an extremely complex scenario. Here, we integrated the information available for most of the distributional patterns that have been recognized in the MTZ. As the case of all the previous works dealing with the biogeography and evolutionary history of the Scarabaeinae dung beetles ( i.e. , Halffter 1962 and subsequent contributions;
Davis et al . 2002
, 2009 , 2016 ; Sole & Scholtz 2010 ;
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
Bai et al . 2015
;
Mlambo et al . 2015
;
Breeschoten et al . 2016
;
Gunter et al . 2016
, 2018 ; Cupello et al ., 2020; Morrone 2020; Schwery & O’Meara 2021 ), our conclusions provide a provisional scenario based on the current knowledge and results, and are subject to new findings and subsequent analyses.

Two shortfalls that must be addressed in future studies are the reduced number of terminals included in the phylogenetic hypotheses, and the underrepresentation of taxonomic groups. With approximately 6580 Scarabaeinae species ( Schoolmeesters 2023 ), the first point seems impossible to overcome in a short term. For example,
Gunter et al . (2016)
included nearly 2.7% of their species richness; while other works have incorporated a more reduced number of taxa: 34 species ( Sole & Scholtz 2010 ), 17 species (
Ahrens et al . 2014
), 75 species (
Mlambo et al . 2015
), 83 species (
Breeschoten et al . 2016
), 127 species (
Gunter et al . 2018
), 94 species (present study). The vast supraspecific diversity of Scarabaeinae is also a challenge. The subfamily encompasses at least 278 genera, 101 subgenera ( Schoolmeesters 2023 ), and several species groups and complexes ( i.e. , Matthews 1961 , 1966, 1972, 1974, Edmonds 1994 ; Zunino & Halffter 1997 ;
Halffter et al . 2019
).

In recent decades, an increase of taxonomical studies (the so-called Taxonomic Revolution) has flourished for the New World Scarabaeinae (
Cupello et al . 2023
). Several taxonomical and nomenclatural changes have been proposed, as well as many new species have been described. Unfortunately, most of those changes have not been updated for the molecular databases. A particular case is that of
Phanaeus
, where the revision of some species groups have led to the discovery of an astonishing cryptic diversity (
Moctezuma et al . 2020a
, 2021; Moctezuma & Halffter 2021;
Lizardo et al . 2022
). It would be helpful if future phylogenetic studies including
Phanaeus species
obtain sequences de novo , because in several cases is not possible to determine which of the currently recognized species pertain to the previously published sequences ( i.e. , Price 2009 ; Gillett & Toussaint 2020 ). It would be advisable to implement phylogenomic tools, but particularly Ultraconserved Elements, which even allow the study of rare and old museum specimens (Daniel & Davis 2023;
Lopes et al . 2023a
).

The origin of Scarabaeinae is currently under debate with two competing hypotheses. On the one hand, a Mesozoic origin associated with the consumption of dinosaur dung ( Jeannel 1942 ; Halffter & Matthews 1966 ;
Davis et al . 2002
, 2009 , 2016 ;
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
Gunter et al . 2016
, 2018 ; Schwery & O’Meara 2021 ). On the other hand, a Cenozoic one with subsequent diversification associated with mammalian dung (
Davis et al . 2002
, 2009 , 2016 ; Sole & Scholtz 2010 ;
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
Bai et al . 2015
;
Mlambo et al . 2015
). The dating of our phylogenetic reconstruction suggests an early Cenozoic origin for the Scarabaeinae . Selection of the calibration point of our phylogeny was based on the study by Tarasov et al . (2016), who revised all the known scarabaeine fossils and concluded that the oldest fossil Scarabaeinae corresponds to
Lobateuchus parisii Montreuil, Génier & Nel, 2010
(Eocenic Oise amber of France, 53 Myr).

Previous studies (
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
Gunter et al . 2016
; Schwery & O’Meara 2021 ) based their points of calibration on Cretaceous fossils ( i.e. ,
Prionocephale deplanate Lin, 1980
and
Juraclopus rohdendorfi Nikolajev, 2005
) that were erroneously attributed to Scarabaeinae or Scarabaeidae (
Davis et al . 2016
; Tarasov et al . 2016;
Neita-Moreno et al . 2019
). Consequently, a Cretaceous origin for Scarabaeinae inferred from the use of these calibration points is not reliable. Certainly, the Scarabaeinae fossil record is extremely scarce and spatio-temporally restricted. Therefore, future discoveries will help improve the knowledge of the evolutionary history and biogeography of this insect group.

The association of Scarabaeinae with the dung of large vertebrates from the Cretaceous (particularly dinosaurs) was originally proposed by Jeannel (1942) and Halffter & Matthews (1966) . This idea has been widely accepted by several authors ( Chin & Gill 1996 ;
Gunter et al . 2016
;
Ebert et al . 2019
;
Giménez-Gómez et al . 2020
;
Lumaret et al . 2020
; Schwery & O’Meara 2021 ). Nevertheless, the hypothetical relationship between Scarabaeinae and dinosaurs is mainly based on speculation and its original proposition was limited by the knowledge available several decades ago; however, it is not well supported by recent evidence. The ichnofossils associated with Scarabaeinae have been fairly questioned (
Bromley et al . 2007
; Davis 2009 ;
Vršanský et al . 2013
; Tarasov et al . 2016). Chin & Gill (1996) reported that a dinosaur coprolite showed evidence of tunneling activity similar to those of Scarabaeinae ; nevertheless,
Vršanský et al . (2013)
concluded that at least some tunnels observed in dinosaur coprolites probably were produced by the activity of extinct cockroaches of the family Blattulidae . It has been proposed that the chemical composition of dinosaur droppings was poorly suitable for Scarabaeinae consumption, as a consequence of the combined voiding of fecal and high nitrate urinary products by the cloacal opening ( Arillo & Ortuño 2008 ;
Davis et al . 2016
). The presence of a cloacal opening in non-avian dinosaurs has been recently confirmed (
Vinther et al . 2021
). Moreover, the consumption of highly nitrate droppings (such as those of birds and reptiles) by extant Scarabaeinae seems to be extremely rare ( Halffter & Matthews 1966 ; Young 1981 ), with ca. 80 records of Scarabaeinae attracted to sauropsid dung (
Lopes et al . 2023b
) versus at least 6850 extant dung beetle species ( Schoolmeesters, 2023 ).
Canthon obliquus Horn, 1894
,
Copris gopheri Hubbard, 1894
and
Onthophagus polyphemi Hubbard, 1894
are among the few cases of New World Scarabaeinae successfully adapted to exploit the droppings produced by reptiles or birds (Young & Goff 1939; Matthews 1961 ; Howden & Cartwright 1963 ; Halffter & Matthews 1966 ; Halffter & Halffter 1989 ).

Some previous phylogenetic hypotheses for Scarabaeinae dung beetles have suggested a Cenozoic origin for this subfamily ( Sole & Scholtz 2010 ;
Mlambo et al . 2015
), which is consistent with our results. Dating of these phylogenies was based on mutation rates and molecular-clock methods. A recent study that used molecular clock dating methods proposed a Mesozoic diversification for Scarabaeinae (
Gunter et al . 2018
). Nevertheless,
Gunter et al . (2018)
suggested that the current fossil record for Scarabaeinae is not reliable, disregarding the seminal work on fossil Scarabaeinae by Tarasov et al . (2016).

Even if Scarabaeinae dung beetles appeared during the Mesozoic, their evolution might be driven by the consumption of mammalian dung ( Arillo & Ortuño 2008 ;
Ahrens et al . 2014
). Indeed, the current knowledge points out that the mammalian crown group likely radiated during the Jurassic (
Upham et al . 2019
). Apparently, Mesozoic mammals were small body-sized and produced small droppings ( Davis 2009 ;
O’Leary et al . 2013
), but this fact would not prevent the consumption of mammalian droppings by Scarabaeinae ( Arillo & Ortuño 2008 ). Indeed, several extant species are specialized on exploiting small dry dung pellets produced by mammals ( Howden & Cartwright 1963 ; Matthews 1972 , 1974 ; Zunino & Halffter 2007 ; Génier 2015 ;
Sánchez-Huerta et al . 2015
, 2018; Kohlmann & Vaz-de-Mello 2018 ). It has been proposed that the ancestors of Scarabaeinae likely were saprophagous beetles that shifted to coprophagy. Subsequently, the explosive radiation of mammals made available highly diversified dung sources that facilitated a rapid radiation in Scarabaeinae (
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
Bai et al . 2015
;
Mlambo et al . 2015
). Saprophagy (
Bai et al . 2015
) or mycetophagy (
Mlambo et al . 2015
) have been proposed as the ancestral feeding preferences. Nonetheless, more studies are needed to test if the consumption of dung produced by mammals, reptiles or birds represents ancestral or derived character states in Scarabaeinae beetles.

From our reconstruction of ancestral areas, the main evidence to support the Mesoamerican patterns is their strong association with the tropical mountain cloud forests of Central America ( Halffter 1978 , 1987 ;
Halffter et al . 2019
), since the taxa that follow these distributional patterns present a high number of endemisms in this particular ecosystem ( Halffter 1978 , 1987 ;
Moctezuma et al . 2018
, 2019, 2023;
Halffter et al . 2019
). The presence of this forest type in the MTZ since the Miocene has been supported by palynological ( Chávez 1993 ; Palacios-Chávez & Rzedowski 1993 ; Graham 1999 ; Martínez-Hernández & Ramírez-Arriaga 1999 ) and phylogeographic ( Ruiz-Sánchez & Ornelas 2014 ) evidence. The Mountain Mesoamerican pattern was proposed specifically for lineages of Neotropical origin ( Halffter 1978 , 1987 ; Halffter & Morrone 2017 ). However,
Halffter et al . (1995)
erroneously included some lineages of northern affinity within this same pattern ( i.e. ,
Onthophagus
), which led to confusion in subsequent studies at the time of classifying these lineages (see
Halffter et al . 2008
; R̂s et al . 2012; Halffter & Morrone 2017 ). As a consequence,
Halffter et al . (2019)
defined the Paleoamerican Mesoamerican pattern to exclusively include the northern lineages, such as
Onthophagus
and
Copris
. Thus, the Holarctic and Neotropical elements that are endemic to the tropical mountain cloud forests were definitively separated in order to prevent future confusion.

The appearance of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt completed the isolation of the Mexican Plateau that had begun with the formation of the Sierra Madre Oriental and Occidental mountains (
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
), which acted preventing the dispersal of Neotropical taxa while favoring that of Holarctic taxa (
Gutiérrez-Velázquez et al . 2012
;
Miguez-Gutiérrez et al . 2013
;
Suárez-Mota et al . 2013
;
Halffter et al . 2019
). Evidence of this phenomenon can be seen in the structure of the communities of Scarabaeinae of the mountains of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt, where numerous species of Neotropical origin can be found in the zones of lower elevation in these mountains, but they decrease in abundance with increasing elevation until disappearing completely, being substituted by Holarctic elements in the high mountain zones (
Halffter et al . 1995
, 2008 ;
Moctezuma et al . 2016
; Halffter & Morrone 2017 ).

The Ancient Neotropical distributional pattern represents a preliminary hypothesis that should be tested by subsequent studies. In this regard, the Ancient Neotropical pattern might include other cenocrons that our results were not able to recognize. So far, we cannot support a Gondwanan ancestry of the Neotropical Scarabaeinae fauna ( Halffter 1962 , 1964 ;
Davis et al . 2002
;
Gunter et al . 2016
, 2018 ; Schwery & O’Meara 2021 ). Instead, Scarabaeinae dung beetles might have originated mainly in the African continent during the early Cenozoic ( Sole & Scholtz 2010 ;
Mlambo et al . 2015
; Cupello et al . 2020; Cupello 2023). After the initial radiation, the Afrotropical ancestors of the Neotropical Scarabaeinae might have dispersed from Africa to South America by transoceanic rafting (Cupello et al . 2020; Cupello 2023). Additional cases of Neotropical biota that probably dispersed from Africa by transoceanic means have been established in mammals (Puox et al . 2006;
de Oliveira et al . 2009
;
Silvestro et al . 2019
), birds (
Voelker et al . 2008
;
Mayr et al . 2011
), reptiles (
Whiting et al . 2006
;
Vidal et al . 2008
), cichlid fishes ( Matschiner 2019 ), weevils (Cristóvão & Lyal 2008), and plants ( Renner 2004 ;
Kistler et al . 2014
).

Previous authors suggested that the ancestors of the Mountain Paleoamerican distribution arose prior to the Miocene, since this period saw the formation of some of the main mountain chains of the MTZ ( Zunino & Halffter 1988 ; Halffter & Morrone 2017 ;
Halffter et al . 2019
). According to our phylogenetic reconstruction, the Mountain Paleoamerican sub-pattern appeared in at least two independent events of speciation during the Miocene, from ancestors of Tropical Paleoamerican distribution. During the Miocene, some mountain chains of the MTZ had a lower elevation, since an important part of the orogeny of the Sierra Madre Occidental developed in this period, as well as the beginning of the formation of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt (
Ferrari et al . 2007
, 2012 ;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). Moreover, the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum caused the appearance of conditions of high temperatures and humidity in the MTZ (
Zachos et al . 2001
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). Under this scenario, it is possible that the ancestors of Tropical Paleoamerican taxa colonized different mountainous zones, dispersing from the adjacent tropical lands, since the elevation and warm-humid climatic conditions did not constitute a limiting factor for their dispersal ( Lobo & Halffter 2000 ;
Halffter et al . 2019
).

Towards the end of the Miocene, the increased elevation of the large mountain chains of the MTZ (
Ferrari et al . 2007
, 2012 ;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
), as well as the temperature decrease caused by the end of the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum (
Zachos et al . 2001
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
), favored the isolation and subsequent diversification of the Paleoamerican lineages that could tolerate the changes in environmental conditions (
Halffter et al . 2019
). The fossil record suggests that after the end of the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum, different temperate mountain forests extended within the MTZ, comprising species of
Pinus
L., 1753,
Quercus
L., 1753,
Juglans
L., 1753, and
Ulmus
L., 1753; among others ( Graham 1999 ;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). These forests are considered the main center of diversification of the Mountain Paleoamerican taxa ( Zunino & Halffter 1988 , 1997 ;
Halffter et al . 2019
). The scarcity of the Mountain Paleoamerican Scarabaeinae in the temperate mountains of Chiapas and Central America can be explained by the sinking of the Tehuantepec Isthmus, which created an area of tropical conditions at the end of the Miocene (
Barrier et al . 1998
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
) that acted impeding the dispersal of elements typical of the temperate mountains from Mexico towards Central America (
Halffter et al . 2019
).

Thanks to the phylogenetic reconstruction of the Scarabaeinae of the MTZ and the paleogeographic scenario suggested by previous authors, we hypothesized that at least two transition zones existed between the Oligocene and Anthropocene between North and South America. We name these zones the Paleo-MTZ (Paleocene-Miocene) and current MTZ (Plio-Pleistocene; Fig. 4 ). Halffter (2019) suggested the existence of at least two different transition zones in the space between North and South America, which are temporally successive but differ geographically and orographically. The main differences we recognize between both transition zones are the existence of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt and the Isthmus of Tehuantepec. The Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt is a Nearctic volcanic area of 1000 km in length that runs from the Pacific to the Atlantic Ocean, between the parallels 18º 30’ N and 21º 30’ N (
Ferrari et al . 2012
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). The Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt completed the volcanic arc that isolated the south of the Mexican Plateau (
Ferrari et al . 2012
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
), preventing the dispersal of tropical taxa and allowing the dispersal and diversification of taxa of cold-temperate zones ( Zunino & Halffter 1988 ; Halffter & Morrone 2017 ). The Isthmus of Tehuantepec is a tropical lowland area located near the triple junction of the North American, Cocos and Caribbean tectonic plates (
Barrier et al . 1998
). This isthmus prevented the dispersal of taxa of cold-temperate zones and favored the dispersal of tropical taxa (
Halffter et al . 2019
; Morrone 2019 ).

The main lineages of Scarabaeinae of the MTZ arose during the Oligocene, giving origin to the Ancient Neotropical and Tropical Paleoamerican distributions. This period saw most of the orogeny of the Sierra Madre Occidental and the Sierra Madre del Sur, the elevation of the Mexican Plateau and the end of the formation of the Sierra Madre Oriental (
Eguiluz de Antuñano et al . 2000
; Manea & Manea 2006 ;
Ferrari et al . 2007
;
Nieto-Samaniego et al . 2007
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). Beringia and the North Atlantic Land Bridge connected North America to Eurasia, allowing dispersal of the Holarctic biota (
Sanmartín et al . 2001
;
Denk et al . 2010
), while Mexico was a peninsula that connected to South America through the proto-Antilles and the oceanic islands formed by the volcanic activity of the Central Panama Volcanic Field ( Halffter & Morrone 2017 ;
Agnolin et al . 2019
;
Buchs et al . 2019
).

During the Oligocene, the Ancient Neotropical lineages were limited in terms of dispersal towards the PaleoMTZ, since in this stage only the “island hoppers” ( i.e. , the Antillean Deltochilini genera that probably represent an ancient over-water dispersal) could successfully disperse from northern South America to southern Mexico( Matthews 1966 ; Halffter & Morrone 2017 ; Crews & Esposito 2020 ). The tropical Holarctic elements ( i.e. ,
Onthophagus
and
Copris
) dispersed from Asia over land through Beringia (
Breeschoten et al . 2016
). This dispersal probably took place at the end of the Oligocene, when the climatic conditions were more warm and humid (
Zanazzi et al . 2007
). As a consequence, the Holarctic elements adapted to the tropical conditions found little limitation to their dispersal towards the Paleo-MTZ, in the geographic space currently occupied by the Mexican Plateau and to the lowlands of southeastern Mexico. During this period, it is probable that some Tropical Paleoamerican “island hoppers” began the dispersal from southern Mexico towards northern South America (as a matter of fact, the members of
Onthophagus
are considered as successful over-water dispersers worldwide), by using the proto-Antilles and the volcanic islands of the Central Panama Volcanic Field as their principal routes of dispersal ( Matthews 1972 ;
Agnolin et al . 2019
;
Buchs et al . 2019
; Crews & Esposito 2020 ).

The transformation of the Paleo-MTZ to the current MTZ probably began during the Miocene. This period saw the beginning or consolidation of some of the main current orographic systems, such as the Mexican Plateau, Sierra Madre Occidental, Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt and the Isthmus of Tehuantepec (
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). Moreover, our results suggest that the greatest process of adaptive radiation of Scarabaeidae occurred during the Miocene, giving origin to most of the distributional patterns ( i.e. , the Mountain Mesoamerican, Mesoamerican Paleoamerican, Mountain Paleoamerican, Mexican Plateau, and Mexican Plateau Paleoamerican). This process of radiation could be the consequence of multiple factors: 1) The formation and consolidation of the orographic systems could have promoted the isolation of the Scarabaeinae of the plateaus and mountains of the MTZ ( Halffter & Morrone 2017 ). 2) The mammalian megafauna of the Paleo-MTZ was present during the Miocene (
Barnosky et al . 2011
; 2016 ), which could have ensured the availability of food and favored diversification of the Scarabaeinae (
Ahrens et al . 2014
;
Bai et al . 2015
;
Breeschoten et al . 2016
). 3) The large-scale generation of terrestrial landscapes occurred in Central America, favoring the connection between North and South America and facilitating dispersal of tropical taxa from northern South America ( Halffter & Morrone 2017 ; Jaramillo 2018 , 2019 ). 4) The end of the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum caused the beginning of a period of global cooling (
Zachos et al . 2001
), which promoted the expansion of temperate biota in the MTZ ( Chávez 1993 ; Palacios-Chávez & Rzedowski 1993 ; Graham 1999 ; Martínez-Hernández & Ramírez-Arriaga 1999 ).

The current MTZ probably consolidated during the Pliocene. In this period, the connection between northern Europe and North America was lost (
Denk et al . 2010
). In addition, the orogenesis of the Sierra Madre Occidental was completed, while the arid scrublands and desert zones expanded in the Mexican Plateau and southeastern United States of America ( Graham 1999 ;
Ferrari et al . 2007
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
). The orogeny of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt was consolidated and the mountainous belt around the Mexican Plateau was completed during this period (
Ferrari et al . 2012
;
Mastretta-Yanes et al . 2015
), preventing the dispersal of lowland tropical elements ( Halffter & Morrone 2017 ). The Central American Land Bridge probably became the main route of dispersal for the tropical elements, since the Panama Seaway probably started to consolidate during the Pliocene (
Montes et al . 2015
; Jaramillo 2018 , 2019 ). Some ancient Holarctic elements of temperate and arid environments ( i.e. , the
Onthophagus chevrolati
and
Onthophagus mexicanus
species groups) probably dispersed from the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt towards the Sierra Madre del Sur, where the Isthmus of Tehuantepec became the main geographic barrier to their dispersal (
Barrier et al . 1998
). With the closure of the Panama Seaway, the marine connections between the Caribbean Sea and the Pacific Ocean were eliminated ( Jaramillo 2018 ;
Agnolin et al . 2019
).
